echo '<h2>Anti-Colonial Resistance</h2>';
echo '<p>Igbo resistance to British colonization began before formal conquest and continued throughout the colonial period. The destruction of the Aro Chukwu oracle in 1902 was met with armed resistance. The Ekumeku movement in Western Igboland mounted sustained guerrilla resistance to British penetration between 1898 and 1911. The Women\'s War of 1929 was the largest anti-colonial uprising in Nigerian history. These were not isolated incidents — they were expressions of a people who understood that their way of life was under existential threat.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Civil War as Struggle</h2>';
echo '<p>The Biafran war was, in Igbo understanding, a struggle for survival — the response of a people who had been massacred in their hundreds of thousands to a state that had failed to protect them. Whatever its military outcome, it shaped a generation\'s understanding of the relationship between power and justice, between the Nigerian state and the Igbo people.</p>';
echo '<h2>Contemporary Struggles</h2>';
echo '<p>The contemporary struggles of Igbo people include the IPOB movement for self-determination, the campaign against marginalization in federal appointments and infrastructure, the environmental justice struggles of Niger Delta communities, and the broader Nigerian youth movements — ENDSARS and its successors — that cut across ethnic lines. These are connected to older struggles by a continuous thread of resistance to illegitimate power.</p>';
